                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d368">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A14/633a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        American Delegate to the General Disarmament Conference</hi> (<persName
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-05-01T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 1, 1934—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>144. The Senate Committee on Foreign Relations today recommended unanimously that
                    the Senate give its advice and consent to <pb facs="0551" n="451"
                        xml:id="pg_451"/> the ratification of the Arms Traffic Convention of 1925.
                    They added the reservation that the ratification should not become effective
                    until the Treaty was ratified by 13 specified powers, among which are the
                    principal arms producing nations.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
